As you all know, the test fails because under specific setup (os: winxp) it's able to set "c:\" as the source path. The test expects the operation to fail with a JavaModelException.
My findings so far: * This is not reproducible using UI since there is a check whether the given path has at least one sement [1]. "c:\" has 0 segments. * It's not that the test passes for you, it's not run at all if you're not on win32. See the first lines of the test [2]. I would replace the check with org.junit.Assume. * Creating a new lib [3], which I assume is being tested here, doesn't throw any checked exceptions including the forementioned JavaModelException. So there is no way this test could fail, unless I'm missing something.
I think the solution here should be limited to adjusting AbstractJavaModelTests.attachSource(...), since JavaCore.newLibraryEntry [3] is an API.

Created attachment 218642 Fix v02
The test failed on my box, not because I'm on WinXp, but because my workspace was on D:\. If it had been on C:\ (just like in the test), it would have thrown a ResourceException[1] (turned into JavaModelException after a while) when creating a link and checking whether its location doesn't overlap with the current workspace[2].
To make the test resistant to that I would make sure the source path is the same as the root of the current workspace location root. This way it will always throw the JME, but at the same time we would check if the NPE is not thrown.
As for explictly catch the NPE I haven't seen such pattern, but can adjust the patch if you have strong feelings about it. However, imho, the test should fail in case of any exception... except for the expected one :)
Speaking of which, ideally the JME catch should be removed as it only add noise. This could be done by making sure we're setting a source path which doesn't overlap with the current workspace, but it's not always possible e.g. if C: is the only drive available. So, I'm afraid we will have to live with it.
PS. The patch contains fixes to typos I found when looking around, do you want me to split the patch so they go into a separate commit?
[1] org.eclipse.core.internal.resources.Resource.assertLinkRequirements(URI, int), line 181 [2] org.eclipse.core.internal.resources.LocationValidator.validateLinkLocationURI(IResource, URI) and org.eclipse.core.internal.utils.FileUtil.isOverlapping(URI, URI)

So, I think we're good.
